Spoiler: It's not a paradox

Reference

Adapted and simplified from Judea Pearl's more technical and complete 2016 resolution of the paradox.

Lord's Formulation

The Question

"A large university is interested in investigating the effects on the students of the diet provided in the university dining halls and any sex differences in these effects. Various types of data are gathered. In particular, the weight of each student at the time of his arrival in September and his weight the following June are recorded."" (Lord 1967, p. 304)

  • How do students' weights differ between the beginning and end of the year?
  • How does sex affect the change in weight?

Data

Male and female students are weighed at the beginning and end of the school year:

  • Blue points/ellipse represent students in Sex B, gold represent Sex A.
  • The dashed line is the diagonal: slope of 1 and intercept of 0.

Analysis

Two stastisticians analyze these data. It was 1967, so the available tools were:

  • ANOVA
  • ANCOVA

Statistician 1

The first statistician compares the mean and variance of the initial vs. final weights in each of the two sexes:

  • In females, the initial weights have the same mean and variance as the final weights
  • Similarly in males, the initial and final weights have the same distribution

Any individual gains or losses cancel each other out, and overall there is negligible change in student weight in either group.

Statistician 1

ANOVA

l_a_anov = aov(Weight ~ Timepoint, filter(l_df_long, Sex == 'F'))
Anova(l_a_anov)

Statistician 2

ANCOVA

The second statistician decides to control for the initial weight of the students.

  • The slopes of the regression lines between initial and final weights are similar in the two dorms, which allows them to compare the intercepts with an ANCOVA:
l_ancov = aov(Gain ~ Sex + Initial, data = l_df)
Anova(l_ancov)

What Even

Who is right? How do we decide?

A Digression: Mediating Variables

Mediation

E.g. does poverty (X) cause cancer (Y)?

Mediation

Maybe poverty (X) increases your exposure to environmental toxins (M), and it's that exposure that causes cancer (Y). I.e. Environmental toxins mediate the effect of poverty on cancer risk.

Mediation

And maybe there are other ways in which poverty affects cancer risk that have nothing to do with environmental toxins.

Mediation

We can think of the effect of X on Y in two ways:

  • Total effect:
    • \(TE = (b + ac) - a\)
    • \(TE = b - a(1 - c)\)

Mediation

We can think of the effect of X on Y in two ways:

  • Total effect:
    • \(TE = (b + ac) - a\)
    • \(TE = b - a(1 - c)\)
  • Direct effect:
    • \(DE = b\)

Construct a mediated dataset

NOT Lord's data

Construct a mediated dataset

# Start with 1000 students
f_0 = rnorm(500, 150, 5)
m_0 = rnorm(500, 160, 5)
  • \(a\): initial weight is higher in males than in females

Construct a mediated dataset

# Start with 1000 students
f_0 = rnorm(500, 150, 5)
m_0 = rnorm(500, 160, 5)

g_fun = function(w_0){
    0.2 * w_0 + rnorm(length(w_0))
}
  • \(a\): initial weight is higher in males than in females
  • \(c\): weight gain is a linear function of initial weight

Construct a mediated dataset

# Start with 1000 students
m_df = (data.frame(Sex = rep(c('F','M'), each = 500),
                Initial = c(f_0, m_0))
        %>% mutate(Gain = g_fun(Initial),
                   Final = Initial + Gain))
  • \(a\): initial weight is higher in males than in females
  • \(c\): weight gain is a linear function of initial weight
  • \(b\): zero. There is no direct effect of sex on weight gain

Mediated Dataset

Statistician 1

The sexes differ in how much weight they gain. We can see it right there in the data.

Statistician 1

  • Statistician 1 is looking at the total effect of sex: \(TE = b - a(1 - c)\)
  • \(b\) was zero, but \(a\) and \(c\) were not

  • They correctly found it to be 0

Context is everything

Who is "correct?"

  • What can you measure?
  • What story are you trying to tell?
  • What is your goal?

Back to Lord's Paradox

Tricksiest. Dataset. Ever.

Tricksiest. Dataset. Ever.

  • Statistician 2 was looking at \(DE = b\)
    • \(b \ne 0\)
    • Sex is significant

Tricksiest. Dataset. Ever.

  • Statistician 2 was looking at \(DE = b\)
    • \(b \ne 0\)
    • Sex is significant
  • Statistician 1 was looking at \(TE = b - a(1 - c)\)
    • \(b \ne 0\)
    • \(b\), \(a\), and \(c\) were chosen s.t. \(b = a(1 - c)\)
    • \(TE = b - a(1 - c) = 0\)
  • The effect of sex on weight gain is anti-mediated by the effect of initial weight.

Antimediation

Lord plotted final weight vs. initial weight

Antimediation

Look at gain vs. initial weight.

Antimediation

  • Males' initial weight is higher than females'
  • Males' weight change intercept is higher than females'
  • Initial weight is negatively associated with gain

Choose the values correctly, and it all cancels.

Should I control for baseline values?

Antimediation

Lord's paradox has nothing to do with baseline values

  • Any pair of variable can do this
  • E.g. sex & body fat
